[src:learning-theory-pac/concept-class] In computational learning theory in mathematics, a **concept** over a domain *X* is a total Boolean function over *X*.
[src:learning-theory-pac/concept-class] A **concept class** is a class of concepts.
[src:learning-theory-pac/concept-class] Concept classes are a subject of computational learning theory.
[src:learning-theory-pac/concept-class] Concept class terminology frequently appears in model theory associated with probably approximately correct (PAC) learning.
[src:learning-theory-pac/concept-class] In this setting, if one takes a set *Y* as a set of (classifier output) labels, and *X* is a set of examples, the map $c:X\to Y$ , i.e. from examples to classifier labels (where $Y=\{0,1\}$ and where *c* is a subset of *X*), *c* is then said to be a *concept*.
[src:learning-theory-pac/concept-class] A *concept class* C is then a collection of such concepts.
[src:learning-theory-pac/concept-class] Given a class of concepts *C*, a subclass *D* is **reachable** if there exists a sample *s* such that *D* contains exactly those concepts in *C* that are extensions to *s*.
[src:learning-theory-pac/concept-class] A *sample* s is a partial function from X to $\{0,1\}$ .
[src:learning-theory-pac/concept-class] Identifying a concept with its characteristic function mapping X to $\{0,1\}$ , it is a special case of a sample.
[src:learning-theory-pac/concept-class] Two samples are *consistent* if they agree on the intersection of their domains.
[src:learning-theory-pac/concept-class] A sample $s'$ *extends* another sample s if the two are consistent and the domain of s is contained in the domain of $s'$ .
[src:learning-theory-pac/concept-class] For any concept $c\in C$ , we call this concept $1/d$ *-good* for a positive integer d if, for all $x\in X$ , at least $1/d$ of the concepts in C agree with c on the classification of x .
[src:learning-theory-pac/concept-class] The *fingerprint dimension* $FD(C)$ of the entire concept class C is the least positive integer d such that every reachable subclass $C'\subseteq C$ contains a concept that is $1/d$ -good for it.
[src:learning-theory-pac/concept-class] This quantity can be used to bound the minimum number of equivalence queries needed to learn a class of concepts according to the following inequality: ${\textstyle FD(C)-1\leq \#EQ(C)\leq \lceil FD(C)\ln(|C|)\rceil }$ .
[src:learning-theory-pac/empirical-risk-minimization] In statistical learning theory, the principle of **empirical risk minimization** defines a family of learning algorithms based on evaluating performance over a known and fixed dataset.
[src:learning-theory-pac/empirical-risk-minimization] The performance over the known set of training data is referred to as the "empirical risk".
[src:learning-theory-pac/empirical-risk-minimization] The following situation is a general setting of many supervised learning problems.
[src:learning-theory-pac/empirical-risk-minimization] There are two spaces of objects X and Y and we would like to learn a function $\ h:X\to Y$ (often called *hypothesis*) which outputs an object $y\in Y$ , given $x\in X$ .
[src:learning-theory-pac/empirical-risk-minimization] To do so, there is a *training set* of n examples $\ (x_{1},y_{1}),\ldots ,(x_{n},y_{n})$ where $x_{i}\in X$ is an input and $y_{i}\in Y$ is the corresponding response that is desired from $h(x_{i})$ .
[src:learning-theory-pac/empirical-risk-minimization] To put it more formally, assuming that there is a joint probability distribution $P(x,y)$ over X and Y , and that the training set consists of n instances $\ (x_{1},y_{1}),\ldots ,(x_{n},y_{n})$ drawn i.i.d. from $P(x,y)$ .
[src:learning-theory-pac/empirical-risk-minimization] The assumption of a joint probability distribution allows for the modelling of uncertainty in predictions (e.g. from noise in data) because y is not a deterministic function of x , but rather a random variable with conditional distribution $P(y|x)$ for a fixed x .
[src:learning-theory-pac/empirical-risk-minimization] It is also assumed that there is a non-negative real-valued loss function $L({\hat {y}},y)$ which measures how different the prediction ${\hat {y}}$ of a hypothesis is from the true outcome y .
[src:learning-theory-pac/empirical-risk-minimization] For classification tasks, these loss functions can be scoring rules.
[src:learning-theory-pac/empirical-risk-minimization] For classification problems, the Bayes classifier is defined to be the classifier minimizing the risk defined with the 0–1 loss function.
[src:learning-theory-pac/empirical-risk-minimization] In general, the risk $R(h)$ cannot be computed because the distribution $P(x,y)$ is unknown to the learning algorithm.
[src:learning-theory-pac/empirical-risk-minimization] Thus, the learning algorithm defined by the empirical risk minimization principle consists in solving the above optimization problem.
[src:learning-theory-pac/empirical-risk-minimization] Guarantees for the performance of empirical risk minimization depend strongly on the function class selected as well as the distributional assumptions made.
[src:learning-theory-pac/empirical-risk-minimization] In general, distribution-free methods are too coarse, and do not lead to practical bounds.
[src:learning-theory-pac/empirical-risk-minimization] However, they are still useful in deriving asymptotic properties of learning algorithms, such as consistency.
[src:learning-theory-pac/empirical-risk-minimization] In particular, distribution-free bounds on the performance of empirical risk minimization given a fixed function class can be derived using bounds on the VC complexity of the function class.
[src:learning-theory-pac/empirical-risk-minimization] For simplicity, considering the case of binary classification tasks, it is possible to bound the probability of the selected classifier, $\phi _{n}$ being much worse than the best possible classifier $\phi ^{*}$ .
[src:learning-theory-pac/empirical-risk-minimization] Consider the risk L defined over the hypothesis class ${\mathcal {C}}$ with growth function ${\mathcal {S}}({\mathcal {C}},n)$ given a dataset of size n .
[src:learning-theory-pac/empirical-risk-minimization] Similar results hold for regression tasks.
[src:learning-theory-pac/empirical-risk-minimization] These results are often based on uniform laws of large numbers, which control the deviation of the empirical risk from the true risk, uniformly over the hypothesis class.
[src:learning-theory-pac/empirical-risk-minimization] It is also possible to show lower bounds on algorithm performance if no distributional assumptions are made.
[src:learning-theory-pac/empirical-risk-minimization] This is sometimes referred to as the *No free lunch theorem*.
[src:learning-theory-pac/empirical-risk-minimization] Even though a specific learning algorithm may provide the asymptotically optimal performance for any distribution, the finite sample performance is always poor for at least one data distribution.
[src:learning-theory-pac/empirical-risk-minimization] This means that no classifier can improve on the error for a given sample size for all distributions.
[src:learning-theory-pac/empirical-risk-minimization] It is further possible to show that the convergence rate of a learning algorithm is poor for some distributions.
[src:learning-theory-pac/empirical-risk-minimization] This result shows that universally good classification rules do not exist, in the sense that the rule must be low quality for at least one distribution.
[src:learning-theory-pac/empirical-risk-minimization] Empirical risk minimization for a classification problem with a 0-1 loss function is known to be an NP-hard problem even for a relatively simple class of functions such as linear classifiers.
[src:learning-theory-pac/empirical-risk-minimization] Nevertheless, it can be solved efficiently when the minimal empirical risk is zero, i.e., data is linearly separable.
[src:learning-theory-pac/empirical-risk-minimization] In the case of convexification, Zhang's lemma majors the excess risk of the original problem using the excess risk of the convexified problem.
[src:learning-theory-pac/empirical-risk-minimization] Minimizing the latter using convex optimization also allow to control the former.
[src:learning-theory-pac/empirical-risk-minimization] Tilted empirical risk minimization is a machine learning technique used to modify standard loss functions like squared error, by introducing a tilt parameter.
[src:learning-theory-pac/empirical-risk-minimization] This parameter dynamically adjusts the weight of data points during training, allowing the algorithm to focus on specific regions or characteristics of the data distribution.
[src:learning-theory-pac/empirical-risk-minimization] Tilted empirical risk minimization is particularly useful in scenarios with imbalanced data or when there is a need to emphasize errors in certain parts of the prediction space.
[src:learning-theory-pac/occam-learning] In computational learning theory, **Occam learning** is a model of algorithmic learning where the objective of the learner is to output a succinct representation of received training data.
[src:learning-theory-pac/occam-learning] This is closely related to probably approximately correct (PAC) learning, where the learner is evaluated on its predictive power of a test set.
[src:learning-theory-pac/occam-learning] Occam learnability implies PAC learning, and for a wide variety of concept classes, the converse is also true: PAC learnability implies Occam learnability.
[src:learning-theory-pac/occam-learning] Occam Learning is named after Occam's razor, which is a principle stating that, given all other things being equal, a shorter explanation for observed data should be favored over a lengthier explanation.
[src:learning-theory-pac/occam-learning] The theory of Occam learning is a formal and mathematical justification for this principle.
[src:learning-theory-pac/occam-learning] It was first shown by Blumer, et al. that Occam learning implies PAC learning, which is the standard model of learning in computational learning theory.
[src:learning-theory-pac/occam-learning] In other words, *parsimony* (of the output hypothesis) implies *predictive power*.
[src:learning-theory-pac/occam-learning] The succinctness of a concept c in concept class ${\mathcal {C}}$ can be expressed by the length $size(c)$ of the shortest bit string that can represent c in ${\mathcal {C}}$ .
[src:learning-theory-pac/occam-learning] Occam learning connects the succinctness of a learning algorithm's output to its predictive power on unseen data.
[src:learning-theory-pac/occam-learning] Let ${\mathcal {C}}$ and ${\mathcal {H}}$ be concept classes containing target concepts and hypotheses respectively.
[src:learning-theory-pac/occam-learning] where n is the maximum length of any sample $x\in S$ .
[src:learning-theory-pac/occam-learning] Here, $error(h)$ is with respect to the concept c and distribution ${\mathcal {D}}$ .
[src:learning-theory-pac/occam-learning] This implies that the algorithm L is also a PAC learner for the concept class ${\mathcal {C}}$ using hypothesis class ${\mathcal {H}}$ .
[src:learning-theory-pac/occam-learning] While the above theorems show that Occam learning is sufficient for PAC learning, it doesn't say anything about *necessity.* Board and Pitt show that, for a wide variety of concept classes, Occam learning is in fact necessary for PAC learning.
[src:learning-theory-pac/occam-learning] They proved that for any concept class that is *polynomially closed under exception lists,* PAC learnability implies the existence of an Occam algorithm for that concept class.
[src:learning-theory-pac/occam-learning] Concept classes that are polynomially closed under exception lists include Boolean formulas, circuits, deterministic finite automata, decision-lists, decision-trees, and other geometrically defined concept classes.
