[src:learning-theory-pac/occam-learning] By the union bound, the probability that there exists a bad hypothesis in ${\mathcal {H}}_{n,m}$ is at most $|{\mathcal {H}}_{n,m}|(1-\epsilon )^{m}$ , which is less than $\delta$ if $\log |{\mathcal {H}}_{n,m}|\leq O(\epsilon m)-\log {\frac {1}{\delta }}$ .
[src:learning-theory-pac/occam-learning] This concludes the proof of the second theorem above.
[src:learning-theory-pac/occam-learning] Using the second theorem, we can prove the first theorem.
[src:learning-theory-pac/occam-learning] Since we have a $(\alpha ,\beta )$ -Occam algorithm, this means that any hypothesis output by L can be represented by at most $(n\cdot size(c))^{\alpha }m^{\beta }$ bits, and thus $\log |{\mathcal {H}}_{n,m}|\leq (n\cdot size(c))^{\alpha }m^{\beta }$ .
[src:learning-theory-pac/occam-learning] Thus, by the Cardinality version Theorem, L will output a consistent hypothesis h with probability at least $1-\delta$ .
[src:learning-theory-pac/occam-learning] This concludes the proof of the first theorem above.
[src:learning-theory-pac/occam-learning] Though Occam and PAC learnability are equivalent, the Occam framework can be used to produce tighter bounds on the sample complexity of classical problems including conjunctions, conjunctions with few relevant variables, and decision lists.
[src:learning-theory-pac/occam-learning] Occam algorithms have also been shown to be successful for PAC learning in the presence of errors, probabilistic concepts, function learning and Markovian non-independent examples.
[src:learning-theory-pac/probably-approximately-correct-learning] In computational learning theory, **probably approximately correct** (**PAC**) **learning** is a framework for mathematical analysis of machine learning.
[src:learning-theory-pac/probably-approximately-correct-learning] It was proposed in 1984 by Leslie Valiant.
[src:learning-theory-pac/probably-approximately-correct-learning] In this framework, the learner receives samples and must select a generalization function (called the *hypothesis*) from a certain class of possible functions.
[src:learning-theory-pac/probably-approximately-correct-learning] The goal is that, with high probability (the "probably" part), the selected function will have low generalization error (the "approximately correct" part).
[src:learning-theory-pac/probably-approximately-correct-learning] The learner must be able to learn the concept given any arbitrary approximation ratio, probability of success, or distribution of the samples.
[src:learning-theory-pac/probably-approximately-correct-learning] The model was later extended to treat noise (misclassified samples).
[src:learning-theory-pac/probably-approximately-correct-learning] An important innovation of the PAC framework is the introduction of computational complexity theory concepts to machine learning.
[src:learning-theory-pac/probably-approximately-correct-learning] In order to give the definition for something that is PAC-learnable, we first have to introduce some terminology.
[src:learning-theory-pac/probably-approximately-correct-learning] For the following definitions, two examples will be used.
[src:learning-theory-pac/probably-approximately-correct-learning] The first is the problem of character recognition given an array of n bits encoding a binary-valued image.
[src:learning-theory-pac/probably-approximately-correct-learning] The other example is the problem of finding an interval that will correctly classify points within the interval as positive and the points outside of the range as negative.
[src:learning-theory-pac/probably-approximately-correct-learning] Let X be a set called the *instance space* or the encoding of all the samples.
[src:learning-theory-pac/probably-approximately-correct-learning] In the character recognition problem, the instance space is $X=\{0,1\}^{n}$ .
[src:learning-theory-pac/probably-approximately-correct-learning] In the interval problem the instance space, X , is the set of all bounded intervals in $\mathbb {R}$ , where $\mathbb {R}$ denotes the set of all real numbers.
[src:learning-theory-pac/probably-approximately-correct-learning] One concept is the set of all patterns of bits in $X=\{0,1\}^{n}$ that encode a picture of the letter "P".
[src:learning-theory-pac/probably-approximately-correct-learning] An example concept from the second example is the set of open intervals, $\{(a,b)\mid 0\leq a\leq \pi /2,\pi \leq b\leq {\sqrt {13}}\}$ , each of which contains only the positive points.
[src:learning-theory-pac/probably-approximately-correct-learning] A *concept class* C is a collection of concepts over X .
[src:learning-theory-pac/probably-approximately-correct-learning] This could be the set of all subsets of the array of bits that are skeletonized 4-connected (width of the font is 1).
[src:learning-theory-pac/probably-approximately-correct-learning] Let $\operatorname {EX} (c,D)$ be a procedure that draws an example, x , using a probability distribution D and gives the correct label $c(x)$ , that is 1 if $x\in c$ and 0 otherwise.
[src:learning-theory-pac/probably-approximately-correct-learning] Further if the above statement for algorithm A is true for every concept $c\in C$ and for every distribution D over X , and for all $0<\epsilon ,\delta <1$ then C is (efficiently) **PAC learnable** (or *distribution-free PAC learnable*).
[src:learning-theory-pac/probably-approximately-correct-learning] We can also say that A is a **PAC learning algorithm** for C .
[src:learning-theory-pac/probably-approximately-correct-learning] *C* is a uniformly Glivenko-Cantelli class.
[src:learning-theory-pac/sample-complexity] The **sample complexity** of a machine learning algorithm represents the number of training-samples that it needs in order to successfully learn a target function.
[src:learning-theory-pac/sample-complexity] More precisely, the sample complexity is the number of training-samples that we need to supply to the algorithm, so that the function returned by the algorithm is within an arbitrarily small error of the best possible function, with probability arbitrarily close to 1.
[src:learning-theory-pac/sample-complexity] The No free lunch theorem, discussed below, proves that, in general, the strong sample complexity is infinite, i.e. that there is no algorithm that can learn the globally-optimal target function using a finite number of training samples.
[src:learning-theory-pac/sample-complexity] However, if we are only interested in a particular class of target functions (e.g., only linear functions) then the sample complexity is finite, and it depends linearly on the VC dimension on the class of target functions.
[src:learning-theory-pac/sample-complexity] Let X be a space which we call the input space, and Y be a space which we call the output space, and let Z denote the product $X\times Y$ .
[src:learning-theory-pac/sample-complexity] For example, in the setting of binary classification, X is typically a finite-dimensional vector space and Y is the set $\{-1,1\}$ .
[src:learning-theory-pac/sample-complexity] Fix a hypothesis space ${\mathcal {H}}$ of functions $h\colon X\to Y$ .
[src:learning-theory-pac/sample-complexity] A learning algorithm over ${\mathcal {H}}$ is a computable map from Z to ${\mathcal {H}}$ .
[src:learning-theory-pac/sample-complexity] In other words, it is an algorithm that takes as input a finite sequence of training samples and outputs a function from X to Y .
[src:learning-theory-pac/sample-complexity] Typical learning algorithms include empirical risk minimization, without or with Tikhonov regularization.
[src:learning-theory-pac/sample-complexity] In our setting, we have $h={\mathcal {A}}(S_{n})$ , where ${\mathcal {A}}$ is a learning algorithm and $S_{n}=((x_{1},y_{1}),\ldots ,(x_{n},y_{n}))\sim \rho ^{n}$ is a sequence of vectors which are all drawn independently from $\rho$ .
[src:learning-theory-pac/sample-complexity] The algorithm ${\mathcal {A}}$ is called **consistent** if ${\mathcal {E}}(h_{n})$ probabilistically converges to ${\mathcal {E}}_{\mathcal {H}}^{*}$ .
[src:learning-theory-pac/sample-complexity] $\Pr _{\rho ^{n}}[{\mathcal {E}}(h_{n})-{\mathcal {E}}_{\mathcal {H}}^{*}\geq \varepsilon ]<\delta .$ The **sample complexity** of ${\mathcal {A}}$ is then the minimum N for which this holds, as a function of $\rho ,\epsilon$ , and $\delta$ .
[src:learning-theory-pac/sample-complexity] We write the sample complexity as $N(\rho ,\epsilon ,\delta )$ to emphasize that this value of N depends on $\rho ,\epsilon$ , and $\delta$ .
[src:learning-theory-pac/sample-complexity] If ${\mathcal {A}}$ is **not consistent**, then we set $N(\rho ,\epsilon ,\delta )=\infty$ .
[src:learning-theory-pac/sample-complexity] If there exists an algorithm for which $N(\rho ,\epsilon ,\delta )$ is finite, then we say that the hypothesis space ${\mathcal {H}}$ is **learnable**.
[src:learning-theory-pac/sample-complexity] In probably approximately correct (PAC) learning, one is concerned with whether the sample complexity is *polynomial*, that is, whether $N(\rho ,\epsilon ,\delta )$ is bounded by a polynomial in $1/\epsilon$ and $1/\delta$ .
[src:learning-theory-pac/sample-complexity] If $N(\rho ,\epsilon ,\delta )$ is polynomial for some learning algorithm, then one says that the hypothesis space ${\mathcal {H}}$ is **PAC-learnable**.
[src:learning-theory-pac/sample-complexity] This is a stronger notion than being learnable.
[src:learning-theory-pac/sample-complexity] One can ask whether there exists a learning algorithm so that the sample complexity is finite in the strong sense, that is, there is a bound on the number of samples needed so that the algorithm can learn any distribution over the input-output space with a specified target error.
[src:learning-theory-pac/sample-complexity] The No Free Lunch Theorem says that without restrictions on the hypothesis space ${\mathcal {H}}$ , this is not the case, i.e., there always exist "bad" distributions for which the sample complexity is arbitrarily large.
[src:learning-theory-pac/sample-complexity] The latter approach leads to concepts such as VC dimension and Rademacher complexity which control the complexity of the space ${\mathcal {H}}$ .
[src:learning-theory-pac/sample-complexity] A smaller hypothesis space introduces more bias into the inference process, meaning that ${\mathcal {E}}_{\mathcal {H}}^{*}$ may be greater than the best possible risk in a larger space.
[src:learning-theory-pac/sample-complexity] However, by restricting the complexity of the hypothesis space it becomes possible for an algorithm to produce more uniformly consistent functions.
[src:learning-theory-pac/sample-complexity] This trade-off leads to the concept of regularization.
[src:learning-theory-pac/sample-complexity] The VC dimension of ${\mathcal {H}}$ is finite.
[src:learning-theory-pac/sample-complexity] 3. ${\mathcal {H}}$ is a uniform Glivenko-Cantelli class.
[src:learning-theory-pac/sample-complexity] This gives a way to prove that certain hypothesis spaces are PAC learnable, and by extension, learnable.
[src:learning-theory-pac/sample-complexity] $X=\mathbb {R} ^{d},Y=\{-1,1\}$ , and let ${\mathcal {H}}$ be the space of affine functions on X , that is, functions of the form $x\mapsto \langle w,x\rangle +b$ for some $w\in \mathbb {R} ^{d},b\in \mathbb {R}$ .
[src:learning-theory-pac/sample-complexity] This is the linear classification with offset learning problem.
[src:learning-theory-pac/sample-complexity] Now, four coplanar points in a square cannot be shattered by any affine function, since no affine function can be positive on two diagonally opposite vertices and negative on the remaining two.
[src:learning-theory-pac/sample-complexity] Thus, the VC dimension of ${\mathcal {H}}$ is $d+1$ , so it is finite.
[src:learning-theory-pac/sample-complexity] It follows by the above characterization of PAC-learnable classes that ${\mathcal {H}}$ is PAC-learnable, and by extension, learnable.
[src:learning-theory-pac/sample-complexity] Suppose ${\mathcal {H}}$ is a class of binary functions (functions to $\{0,1\}$ ).
[src:learning-theory-pac/sample-complexity] Moreover, any $(\epsilon ,\delta )$ -PAC-learning algorithm for ${\mathcal {H}}$ must have sample-complexity: $N=\Omega {\bigg (}{\frac {VC({\mathcal {H}})+\ln {1 \over \delta }}{\epsilon }}{\bigg )}$ Thus, the sample-complexity is a linear function of the VC dimension of the hypothesis space.
[src:learning-theory-pac/sample-complexity] Suppose ${\mathcal {H}}$ is a class of real-valued functions with range in $[0,T]$ .
[src:learning-theory-pac/sample-complexity] In addition to the supervised learning setting, sample complexity is relevant to semi-supervised learning problems including active learning, where the algorithm can ask for labels to specifically chosen inputs in order to reduce the cost of obtaining many labels.
[src:learning-theory-pac/sample-complexity] The concept of sample complexity also shows up in reinforcement learning, online learning, and unsupervised algorithms, e.g. for dictionary learning.
[src:learning-theory-pac/sample-complexity] A high sample complexity means that many calculations are needed for running a Monte Carlo tree search.
[src:learning-theory-pac/sample-complexity] It is equivalent to a model-free brute force search in the state space.
[src:learning-theory-pac/sample-complexity] In contrast, a high-efficiency algorithm has a low sample complexity.
[src:learning-theory-pac/sample-complexity] Possible techniques for reducing the sample complexity are metric learning and model-based reinforcement learning.
[src:learning-theory-pac/vapnik-chervonenkis-dimension] In Vapnik–Chervonenkis theory, the **Vapnik–Chervonenkis (VC) dimension** is a measure of the size (capacity, complexity, expressive power, richness, or flexibility) of a class of sets.
[src:learning-theory-pac/vapnik-chervonenkis-dimension] The notion can be extended to classes of binary functions.
[src:learning-theory-pac/vapnik-chervonenkis-dimension] It is defined as the cardinality of the largest set of points that the function class can shatter—that is, for which all possible binary labelings can be realized by some function in the class.
[src:learning-theory-pac/vapnik-chervonenkis-dimension] It was originally defined by Vladimir Vapnik and Alexey Chervonenkis.
[src:learning-theory-pac/vapnik-chervonenkis-dimension] Informally, the capacity of a classification model is related to how complicated it can be.
[src:learning-theory-pac/vapnik-chervonenkis-dimension] For example, consider the thresholding of a high-degree polynomial: if the polynomial evaluates above zero, that point is classified as positive, otherwise as negative.
[src:learning-theory-pac/vapnik-chervonenkis-dimension] A high-degree polynomial can be wiggly, so that it can fit a given set of training points well.
[src:learning-theory-pac/vapnik-chervonenkis-dimension] A much simpler alternative is to threshold a linear function.
[src:learning-theory-pac/vapnik-chervonenkis-dimension] This function may not fit the training set well, because it has a low capacity.
[src:learning-theory-pac/vapnik-chervonenkis-dimension] This notion of capacity is made rigorous below.
[src:learning-theory-pac/vapnik-chervonenkis-dimension] Let ${\mathcal {C}}=\{C\}_{C\in {\mathcal {C}}}$ be a family of sets (also called set family, collection of sets, or set of sets) and X be a set.
[src:learning-theory-pac/vapnik-chervonenkis-dimension] Here typically X and each $C\in {\mathcal {C}}$ are subsets of a big "universe" of possibilities U where intersection takes place.
[src:learning-theory-pac/vapnik-chervonenkis-dimension] We say that a set X is *shattered* by ${\mathcal {C}}$ if ${\mathcal {P}}(X)={\mathcal {C}}\cap X$ i.e. the set of intersections contains (hence is equal to the set of) all the subsets of X .
[src:learning-theory-pac/vapnik-chervonenkis-dimension] The *VC dimension* D of ${\mathcal {C}}$ is the cardinality of the largest set that is shattered by ${\mathcal {C}}$ .
[src:learning-theory-pac/vapnik-chervonenkis-dimension] If arbitrarily large sets can be shattered, the VC dimension of ${\mathcal {C}}$ is $\infty$ .
[src:learning-theory-pac/vapnik-chervonenkis-dimension] Consider a binary classification model f with some parameter vector $\theta$ , a set of generally positioned data points $x_{1},x_{2},\ldots ,x_{n}$ .
[src:learning-theory-pac/vapnik-chervonenkis-dimension] We say that the model f shatters $x_{1},x_{2},\ldots ,x_{n}$ if, for every assignment of labels to those points, there exists a vector $\theta$ such that the model f makes no errors when evaluating that set of data points.
[src:learning-theory-pac/vapnik-chervonenkis-dimension] The VC dimension of a model f is the maximum number of points that can be arranged so that f shatters them.
[src:learning-theory-pac/vapnik-chervonenkis-dimension] More formally, it is the maximum cardinal D such that there exists a generally positioned data point set of cardinality D that can be shattered by f .
[src:learning-theory-pac/vapnik-chervonenkis-dimension] 2. f is a single-parametric threshold classifier on real numbers; i.e., for a certain threshold $\theta$ , the classifier $f_{\theta }$ returns 1 if the input number is larger than $\theta$ and 0 otherwise.
[src:learning-theory-pac/vapnik-chervonenkis-dimension] The VC dimension of f is 1 because: (a) It can shatter a single point.
[src:learning-theory-pac/vapnik-chervonenkis-dimension] For every point x , a classifier $f_{\theta }$ labels it as 0 if $\theta >x$ and labels it as 1 if $\theta <x$ .
[src:learning-theory-pac/vapnik-chervonenkis-dimension] (b) It cannot shatter all the sets with two points.
[src:learning-theory-pac/vapnik-chervonenkis-dimension] For every set of two numbers, if the smaller is labeled 1, then the larger must also be labeled 1, so not all labelings are possible.
[src:learning-theory-pac/vapnik-chervonenkis-dimension] 3. f is a single-parametric interval classifier on real numbers; i.e., for a certain parameter $\theta$ , the classifier $f_{\theta }$ returns 1 if the input number is in the interval $[\theta ,\theta +4]$ and 0 otherwise.
[src:learning-theory-pac/vapnik-chervonenkis-dimension] The VC dimension of f is 2 because: (a) It can shatter some sets of two points.
[src:learning-theory-pac/vapnik-chervonenkis-dimension] (b) It cannot shatter any set of three points.
[src:learning-theory-pac/vapnik-chervonenkis-dimension] For every set of three numbers, if the smallest and the largest are labeled 1, then the middle one must also be labeled 1, so not all labelings are possible.
[src:learning-theory-pac/vapnik-chervonenkis-dimension] 4. f is a straight line as a classification model on points in a two-dimensional plane (this is the model used by a perceptron).
[src:learning-theory-pac/vapnik-chervonenkis-dimension] The line should separate positive data points from negative data points.
[src:learning-theory-pac/vapnik-chervonenkis-dimension] There exist sets of 3 points that can indeed be shattered using this model (any 3 points that are not collinear can be shattered).
[src:learning-theory-pac/vapnik-chervonenkis-dimension] However, no set of 4 points can be shattered: by Radon's theorem, any four points can be partitioned into two subsets with intersecting convex hulls, so it is not possible to separate one of these two subsets from the other.
[src:learning-theory-pac/vapnik-chervonenkis-dimension] Thus, the VC dimension of this particular classifier is 3.
[src:learning-theory-pac/vapnik-chervonenkis-dimension] It is important to remember that while one can choose any arrangement of points, the arrangement of those points cannot change when attempting to shatter for some label assignment.
[src:learning-theory-pac/vapnik-chervonenkis-dimension] Note, only 3 of the 23 = 8 possible label assignments are shown for the three points.
[src:learning-theory-pac/vapnik-chervonenkis-dimension] 5. f is a single-parametric sine classifier, i.e., for a certain parameter $\theta$ , the classifier $f_{\theta }$ returns 1 if the input number x has $\sin(\theta x)>0$ and 0 otherwise.
[src:learning-theory-pac/vapnik-chervonenkis-dimension] The VC dimension of f is infinite, since it can shatter any finite subset of the set $\{2^{-m}\mid m\in \mathbb {N} \}$ .
[src:learning-theory-pac/vapnik-chervonenkis-dimension] The VC dimension can predict a probabilistic upper bound on the test error of a classification model.
[src:learning-theory-pac/vapnik-chervonenkis-dimension] where D is the VC dimension of the classification model, $0<\eta \leqslant 1$ , and N is the size of the training set (restriction: this formula is valid when $D\ll N$ .
[src:learning-theory-pac/vapnik-chervonenkis-dimension] When D is larger, the test-error may be much higher than the training-error.
[src:learning-theory-pac/vapnik-chervonenkis-dimension] The VC dimension also appears in sample-complexity bounds.
[src:learning-theory-pac/vapnik-chervonenkis-dimension] samples, where $\varepsilon$ is the learning error and $\delta$ is the failure probability.
[src:learning-theory-pac/vapnik-chervonenkis-dimension] Thus, the sample-complexity is a linear function of the VC dimension of the hypothesis space.
[src:learning-theory-pac/vapnik-chervonenkis-dimension] The VC dimension is one of the critical parameters in the size of ε-nets, which determines the complexity of approximation algorithms based on them; range sets without finite VC dimension may not have finite ε-nets at all.
[src:learning-theory-pac/vapnik-chervonenkis-dimension] The VC dimension of the dual set-family of ${\mathcal {C}}$ is strictly less than $2^{\operatorname {vc} ({\mathcal {C}})+1}$ , and this is best possible.
[src:learning-theory-pac/vapnik-chervonenkis-dimension] The VC dimension of a finite set-family ${\mathcal {C}}$ is at most $\log _{2}|{\mathcal {C}}|$ .
[src:learning-theory-pac/vapnik-chervonenkis-dimension] This is because $|{\mathcal {C}}\cap X|\leq |X|$ by definition.
[src:learning-theory-pac/vapnik-chervonenkis-dimension] Given a set-family ${\mathcal {C}}$ , define ${\mathcal {C}}_{s}$ as a set-family that contains all intersections of s elements of ${\mathcal {C}}$ .
[src:learning-theory-pac/vapnik-chervonenkis-dimension] Given a set-family ${\mathcal {C}}$ and an element $C_{0}\in {\mathcal {C}}$ , define ${\mathcal {C}}\,\Delta C_{0}:=\{C\,\Delta C_{0}\mid C\in H\}$ where $\Delta$ denotes symmetric set difference.
[src:learning-theory-pac/vapnik-chervonenkis-dimension] The VC dimension of a finite projective plane is 2.
[src:learning-theory-pac/vapnik-chervonenkis-dimension] Suppose we have a base class B of simple classifiers, whose VC dimension is D .
[src:learning-theory-pac/vapnik-chervonenkis-dimension] We can construct a more powerful classifier by combining several different classifiers from B ; this technique is called boosting.
[src:learning-theory-pac/vapnik-chervonenkis-dimension] The VC dimension is defined for spaces of binary functions (functions to {0,1}).
[src:learning-theory-pac/vapnik-chervonenkis-dimension] Several generalizations have been suggested for spaces of non-binary functions.
